# Input
```ts
// `Identity<string>` and `Identity<number>` substitute to `string` and `number`, so each conversion is redundant.
type Identity<T> = T;
declare const text: Identity<string>;
String(text);
text.toString();
"" + text;
declare const count: Identity<number>;
+count;

```

# Diagnostics
```
invalidGenericTypeAlias.ts:4:1 lint/nursery/noUselessTypeConversion ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

  i Avoid calling `String()` on a string value.
  
    2 │ type Identity<T> = T;
    3 │ declare const text: Identity<string>;
  > 4 │ String(text);
      │ ^^^^^^
    5 │ text.toString();
    6 │ "" + text;
  
  i This expression already evaluates to a string.
  
  i Remove the conversion and use the value directly.
  
  i Redundant conversions make it harder to see that the value already has the expected string type.
  
